"potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-63851","SV-78341","CCI-000213"],"reference_identifier":"3648","uuid":"0cd38500-cbf8-4bd7-a6df-5eac6bcd594f","stig_uuid":"af950999-fa42-4c61-9340-039117433de8","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Windows10_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 2CE4F196629C75514C479FD82FC30CD74930F274\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'The Allow log on locally user right must only be assigned to the Administrators and Users groups.' is not present or not in use on this the Windows 10 workstation."},{"group_id_src":"V-220960","group_tree":[{"id":"V-220960","title":"SRG-OS-000324-GPOS-00125","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-220960","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000324-GPOS-00125","rule_id_src":"SV-220960r958726_rule","rule_id":"SV-220960","rule_version":"WN10-UR-000030","rule_title":"The Back up files and directories user right must only be assigned to the Administrators group.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> User Rights Assignment >> \"Back up files and directories\" to only include the following groups or accounts:\n\nAdministrators","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the effective setting in Local Group Policy Editor.\nRun \"gpedit.msc\".\n\nNavigate to Local Computer Policy >> Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> User Rights Assignment.\n\nIf any groups or accounts other than the following are granted the \"Back up files and directories\" user right, this is a finding:\n\nAdministrators","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Inappropriate granting of user rights can provide system, administrative, and other high level capabilities.\n\nAccounts with the \"Back up files and directories\" user right can circumvent file and directory permissions and could allow access to sensitive data.\"","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-63853","SV-78343","CCI-002235"],"reference_identifier":"2535","uuid":"415a2266-2fe1-4553-b481-f09cc242d7dc","stig_uuid":"af950999-fa42-4c61-9340-039117433de8","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":""},{"group_id_src":"V-220961","group_tree":[{"id":"V-220961","title":"SRG-OS-000324-GPOS-00125","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-220961","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000324-GPOS-00125","rule_id_src":"SV-220961r958726_rule","rule_id":"SV-220961","rule_version":"WN10-UR-000035","rule_title":"The Change the system time user right must only be assigned to Administrators and Local Service and NT SERVICE\\autotimesvc.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> User Rights Assignment >> \"Change the system time\" to only include the following groups or accounts:\n\nAdministrators\nLOCAL SERVICE\nNT SERVICE\\autotimesvc is added in v1909 cumulative update.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the effective setting in Local Group Policy Editor.\nRun \"gpedit.msc\".\n\nNavigate to Local Computer Policy >> Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> User Rights Assignment.\n\nIf any groups or accounts other than the following are granted the \"Change the system time\" user right, this is a finding:\n\nAdministrators\nLOCAL SERVICE\nNT SERVICE\\autotimesvc is added in v1909 cumulative update.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Inappropriate granting of user rights can provide system, administrative, and other high level capabilities.\n\nAccounts with the \"Change the system time\" user right can change the system time, which can impact authentication, as well as affect time stamps on event log entries.\n\nThe NT SERVICE\\autotimesvc is added in v1909 cumulative update.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-63855","SV-78345","CCI-002235"],"reference_identifier":"2930","uuid":"36116476-be37-48ca-874e-37d551d32b30","stig_uuid":"af950999-fa42-4c61-9340-039117433de8","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Windows10_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 3DCD263F44EAEC88D1B0743326204E47554A79E9\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'The Change the system time user right must only be assigned to Administrators and Local Service and NT SERVICE\\autotimesvc.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows 10 workstation."},{"group_id_src":"V-220962","group_tree":[{"id":"V-220962","title":"SRG-OS-000324-GPOS-00125","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-220962","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000324-GPOS-00125","rule_id_src":"SV-220962r958726_rule","rule_id":"SV-220962","rule_version":"WN10-UR-000040","rule_title":"The Create a pagefile user right must only be assigned to the Administrators group.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> User Rights Assignment >> \"Create a pagefile\" to only include the following groups or accounts:\n\nAdministrators","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the effective setting in Local Group Policy Editor.\nRun \"gpedit.msc\".\n\nNavigate to Local Computer Policy >> Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> User Rights Assignment.\n\nIf any groups or accounts other than the following are granted the \"Create a pagefile\" user right, this is a finding:\n\nAdministrators","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Inappropriate granting of user rights can provide system, administrative, and other high level capabilities.\n\nAccounts with the \"Create a pagefile\" user right can change the size of a pagefile, which could affect system performance.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-78347","V-63857","CCI-002235"],"reference_identifier":"1135","uuid":"3ce1699f-5582-4526-a65e-566741d595ee","stig_uuid":"af950999-fa42-4c61-9340-039117433de8","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Windows10_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: E03D00A9316F6FEE7F116FE66602EB240E112BA6\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'The Create a pagefile user right must only be assigned to the Administrators group.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows 10 workstation."},{"group_id_src":"V-220963","group_tree":[{"id":"V-220963","title":"SRG-OS-000324-GPOS-00125","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-220963","severity":"high","group_title":"SRG-OS-000324-GPOS-00125","rule_id_src":"SV-220963r958726_rule","rule_id":"SV-220963","rule_version":"WN10-UR-000045","rule_title":"The Create a token object user right must not be assigned to any groups or accounts.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> User Rights Assignment >> \"Create a token object\" to be defined but containing no entries (blank).","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the effective setting in Local Group Policy Editor.\nRun \"gpedit.msc\".\n\nNavigate to Local Computer Policy >> Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> User Rights Assignment.\n\nIf any groups or accounts are granted the \"Create a token object\" user right, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Inappropriate granting of user rights can provide system, administrative, and other high level capabilities.\n\nThe \"Create a token object\" user right allows a process to create an access token. This could be used to provide elevated rights and compromise a system.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-63859","SV-78349","CCI-002235"],"reference_identifier":"6469","uuid":"72cff317-e277-4ff6-a90d-7c9fff4f3fb0","stig_uuid":"af950999-fa42-4c61-9340-039117433de8","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Windows10_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 77E893091313639CB39D945005D7DEA478B00391\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'The Create a token object user right must not be assigned to any groups or accounts.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows 10 workstation."},{"group_id_src":"V-220964","group_tree":[{"id":"V-220964","title":"SRG-OS-000324-GPOS-00125","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-220964","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000324-GPOS-00125","rule_id_src":"SV-220964r958726_rule","rule_id":"SV-220964","rule_version":"WN10-UR-000050","rule_title":"The Create global objects user right must only be assigned to Administrators, Service, Local Service, and Network Service.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> User Rights Assignment >> \"Create global objects\" to only include the following groups or accounts:\n\nAdministrators\nLOCAL SERVICE\nNETWORK SERVICE\nSERVICE","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the effective setting in Local Group Policy Editor.\nRun \"gpedit.msc\".\n\nNavigate to Local Computer Policy >> Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> User Rights Assignment.\n\nIf any groups or accounts other than the following are granted the \"Create global objects\" user right, this is a finding:\n\nAdministrators\nLOCAL SERVICE\nNETWORK SERVICE\nSERVICE","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Inappropriate granting of user rights can provide system, administrative, and other high level capabilities.\n\nAccounts with the \"Create global objects\" user right can create objects that are available to all sessions, which could affect processes in other users' sessions.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-63861","SV-78351","CCI-002235"],"reference_identifier":"3013","uuid":"b0d7b0d2-0106-4bfc-86c0-3eca27a36e4d","stig_uuid":"af950999-fa42-4c61-9340-039117433de8","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Windows10_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 1FD81FD710E50EC0260251221192FC02B867FAAD\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'The Create global objects user right must only be assigned to Administrators, Service, Local Service, and Network Service.' matches the expected value on the Windows 10 workstation."},{"group_id_src":"V-220965","group_tree":[{"id":"V-220965","title":"SRG-OS-000324-GPOS-00125","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-220965","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000324-GPOS-00125","rule_id_src":"SV-220965r958726_rule","rule_id":"SV-220965","rule_version":"WN10-UR-000055","rule_title":"The Create permanent shared objects user right must not be assigned to any groups or accounts.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> User Rights Assignment >> \"Create permanent shared objects\" to be defined but containing no entries (blank).","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the effective setting in Local Group Policy Editor.\nRun \"gpedit.msc\".\n\nNavigate to Local Computer Policy >> Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> User Rights Assignment.\n\nIf any groups or accounts are granted the \"Create permanent shared objects\" user right, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Inappropriate granting of user rights can provide system, administrative, and other high level capabilities.\n\nAccounts with the \"Create permanent shared objects\" user right could expose sensitive data by creating shared objects.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-63863","SV-78353","CCI-002235"],"reference_identifier":"4126","uuid":"36c3e607-1c75-4921-b27e-6e08953be63a","stig_uuid":"af950999-fa42-4c61-9340-039117433de8","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Windows10_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: C1F5F15FEE4840CDBB04B45EBA605AAEBAC35598\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'The Create permanent shared objects user right must not be assigned to any groups or accounts.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows 10 workstation."},{"group_id_src":"V-220966","group_tree":[{"id":"V-220966","title":"SRG-OS-000324-GPOS-00125","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-220966","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000324-GPOS-00125","rule_id_src":"SV-220966r958726_rule","rule_id":"SV-220966","rule_version":"WN10-UR-000060","rule_title":"The Create symbolic links user right must only be assigned to the Administrators group.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> User Rights Assignment >> \"Create symbolic links\" to only include the following groups or accounts:\n\nAdministrators","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the effective setting in Local Group Policy Editor.\nRun \"gpedit.msc\".\n\nNavigate to Local Computer Policy >> Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> User Rights Assignment.\n\nIf any groups or accounts other than the following are granted the \"Create symbolic links\" user right, this is a finding:\n\nAdministrators\n\nIf the workstation has an approved use of Hyper-V, such as being used as a dedicated admin workstation using Hyper-V to separate administration and standard user functions, \"NT VIRTUAL MACHINES\\VIRTUAL MACHINE\" may be assigned this user right and is not a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Inappropriate granting of user rights can provide system, administrative, and other high level capabilities.\n\nAccounts with the \"Create symbolic links\" user right can create pointers to other objects, which could potentially expose the system to attack.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-78355","V-63865","CCI-002235"],"reference_identifier":"5612","uuid":"4b545408-5ed2-4b5c-9d12-0935ae2f4314","stig_uuid":"af950999-fa42-4c61-9340-039117433de8","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Windows10_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 54A5F0B96BE49ADA8CCF5A2E7D52B73B389C1574\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'The Create symbolic links user right must only be assigned to the Administrators group.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows 10 workstation."},{"group_id_src":"V-220967","group_tree":[{"id":"V-220967","title":"SRG-OS-000324-GPOS-00125","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-220967","severity":"high","group_title":"SRG-OS-000324-GPOS-00125","rule_id_src":"SV-220967r958726_rule","rule_id":"SV-220967","rule_version":"WN10-UR-000065","rule_title":"The Debug programs user right must only be assigned to the Administrators group.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> User Rights Assignment >> \"Debug programs\" to only include the following groups or accounts:\n\nAdministrators","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the effective setting in Local Group Policy Editor.\nRun \"gpedit.msc\".\n\nNavigate to Local Computer Policy >> Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> User Rights Assignment.\n\nIf any groups or accounts other than the following are granted the \"Debug Programs\" user right, this is a finding:\n\nAdministrators","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Inappropriate granting of user rights can provide system, administrative, and other high level capabilities.\n\nAccounts with the \"Debug Programs\" user right can attach a debugger to any process or to the kernel, providing complete access to sensitive and critical operating system components.  This right is given to Administrators in the default configuration.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-63869","SV-78359","CCI-002235"],"reference_identifier":"5726","uuid":"00e3c68c-3ffc-4b43-a148-5e9789b42c06","stig_uuid":"af950999-fa42-4c61-9340-039117433de8","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Windows10_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 075EFEF639A6CADA47FD1D30BA039DC9381D2DC8\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'The Debug programs user right must only be assigned to the Administrators group.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows 10 workstation."},{"group_id_src":"V-220968","group_tree":[{"id":"V-220968","title":"SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-220968","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048","rule_id_src":"SV-220968r1137691_rule","rule_id":"SV-220968","rule_version":"WN10-UR-000070","rule_title":"The Deny access to this computer from the network user right on workstations must be configured to prevent access from highly privileged domain accounts and local accounts on domain systems and unauthenticated access on all systems.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> User Rights Assignment >> \"Deny access to this computer from the network\" to include the following.\n\nDomain Systems Only:\nEnterprise Admins group\nDomain Admins group\nLocal account (see Note below)\n\nAll Systems:\nGuests group\n\nPrivileged Access Workstations (PAWs) dedicated to the management of Active Directory are exempt from denying the Enterprise Admins and Domain Admins groups. (See the Windows Privileged Access Workstation STIG for PAW requirements.)\n\nNote: \"Local account\" is a built-in security group used to assign user rights and permissions to all local accounts.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the effective setting in Local Group Policy Editor.\n\nRun \"gpedit.msc\".\n\nNavigate to Local Computer Policy >> Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> User Rights Assignment.\n\nIf the following groups or accounts are not defined for the \"Deny access to this computer from the network\" right, this is a finding:\n\nDomain Systems Only:\nEnterprise Admins group\nDomain Admins group\nLocal account (see Note below)\n\nAll Systems:\nGuests group\n\nPrivileged Access Workstations (PAWs) dedicated to the management of Active Directory are exempt from denying the Enterprise Admins and Domain Admins groups. (See the Windows Privileged Access Workstation STIG for PAW requirements.)\n\nNote: \"Local account\" is a built-in security group used to assign user rights and permissions to all local accounts.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Inappropriate granting of user rights can provide system, administrative, and other high-level capabilities.\n\nThe \"Deny access to this computer from the network\" right defines the accounts that are prevented from logging on from the network.\n\nIn an Active Directory Domain, denying logons to the Enterprise Admins and Domain Admins groups on lower trust systems helps mitigate the risk of privilege escalation from credential theft attacks, which could lead to the compromise of an entire domain.\n\nLocal accounts on domain-joined systems must also be assigned this right to decrease the risk of lateral movement resulting from credential theft attacks.\n\nThe Guests group must be assigned this right to prevent unauthenticated access.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-63871","SV-78361","CCI-000213"],"reference_identifier":"2933","uuid":"4dc8b844-131a-4d2f-8f8a-f1e229b24a85","stig_uuid":"af950999-fa42-4c61-9340-039117433de8","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Windows10_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: F111CE68E7B69EC45580BBE4DF309BE43F2FDD2C\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'The Deny access to this computer from the network user right on workstations must be configured to prevent access from highly privileged domain accounts and local accounts on domain systems and unauthenticated access on all systems.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows 10 workstation."},{"group_id_src":"V-220969","group_tree":[{"id":"V-220969","title":"SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-220969","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048","rule_id_src":"SV-220969r1137691_rule","rule_id":"SV-220969","rule_version":"WN10-UR-000075","rule_title":"The \"Deny log on as a batch job\" user right on domain-joined workstations must be configured to prevent access from highly privileged domain accounts.","fix_text":"This requirement is applicable to domain-joined systems. For standalone or nondomain-joined systems, this is NA.\n\nConfigure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> User Rights Assignment >> \"Deny log on as a batch job\" to include the following:\n\nDomain Systems Only:\nEnterprise Admin Group\nDomain Admin Group","weight":"10.0","check_content":"This requirement is applicable to domain-joined systems. For standalone or nondomain-joined systems, this is NA.\n\nVerify the effective setting in Local Group Policy Editor.\nRun \"gpedit.msc\".\n\nNavigate to Local Computer Policy >> Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> User Rights Assignment.\n\nIf the following groups or accounts are not defined for the \"Deny log on as a batch job\" right, this is a finding.\n\nDomain Systems Only:\nEnterprise Admin Group\nDomain Admin Group","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Inappropriate granting of user rights can provide system, administrative, and other high-level capabilities.\n\nThe \"Deny log on as a batch job\" right defines accounts that are prevented from logging on to the system as a batch job, such as Task Scheduler.\n\nIn an Active Directory Domain, denying logons to the Enterprise Admins and Domain Admins groups on lower-trust systems helps mitigate the risk of privilege escalation from credential theft attacks that could lead to the compromise of an entire domain.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-78363","V-63873","CCI-000213"],"reference_identifier":"4895","uuid":"7b499f38-53b0-4d72-b755-af2ab712154d","stig_uuid":"af950999-fa42-4c61-9340-039117433de8","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Windows10_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 4A8C032992CA38923E409E716AB0BC24C20F2096\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'The \"Deny log on as a batch job\" user right on domain-joined workstations must be configured to prevent access from highly privileged domain accounts.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows 10 workstation."},{"group_id_src":"V-220970","group_tree":[{"id":"V-220970","title":"SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-220970","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048","rule_id_src":"SV-220970r1137691_rule","rule_id":"SV-220970","rule_version":"WN10-UR-000080","rule_title":"The Deny log on as a service user right on Windows 10 domain-joined workstations must be configured to prevent access from highly privileged domain accounts.","fix_text":"This requirement is applicable to domain-joined systems. For standalone or nondomain-joined systems, this is NA.\n\nConfigure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> User Rights Assignment >> \"Deny log on as a service\" to include the following:\n\nDomain Systems Only:\nEnterprise Admins Group\nDomain Admins Group","weight":"10.0","check_content":"This requirement is applicable to domain-joined systems. For standalone or nondomain-joined systems, this is NA.\n\nVerify the effective setting in Local Group Policy Editor.\nRun \"gpedit.msc\".\n\nNavigate to Local Computer Policy >> Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> User Rights Assignment.\n\nIf the following groups or accounts are not defined for the \"Deny log on as a service\" right , this is a finding.\n\nDomain Systems Only:\nEnterprise Admins Group\nDomain Admins Group","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Inappropriate granting of user rights can provide system, administrative, and other high level capabilities.\n\nThe \"Deny log on as a service\" right defines accounts that are denied log on as a service.\n\nIn an Active Directory Domain, denying logons to the Enterprise Admins and Domain Admins groups on lower trust systems helps mitigate the risk of privilege escalation from credential theft attacks which could lead to the compromise of an entire domain.\n\nIncorrect configurations could prevent services from starting and result in a DoS.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-63875","SV-78365","CCI-000213"],"reference_identifier":"4437","uuid":"94ca10cb-7390-4765-b959-7bcf61224fa2","stig_uuid":"af950999-fa42-4c61-9340-039117433de8","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Windows10_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 16E5C606B9A7CE24995E4F6314C3B3B99B09486C\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'The Deny log on as a service user right on Windows 10 domain-joined workstations must be configured to prevent access from highly privileged domain accounts.' matches the expected value on the Windows 10 workstation."},{"group_id_src":"V-220971","group_tree":[{"id":"V-220971","title":"SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-220971","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048","rule_id_src":"SV-220971r1137691_rule","rule_id":"SV-220971","rule_version":"WN10-UR-000085","rule_title":"The Deny log on locally user right on workstations must be configured to prevent access from highly privileged domain accounts on domain systems and unauthenticated access on all systems.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> User Rights Assignment >> \"Deny log on locally\" to include the following.\n\nDomain Systems Only:\nEnterprise Admins Group\nDomain Admins Group\n\nPrivileged Access Workstations (PAWs) dedicated to the management of Active Directory are exempt from denying the Enterprise Admins and Domain Admins groups. (See the Windows Privileged Access Workstation STIG for PAW requirements.)\n\nAll Systems:\nGuests Group","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the effective setting in Local Group Policy Editor.\n\nRun \"gpedit.msc\".\n\nNavigate to Local Computer Policy >> Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> User Rights Assignment.\n\nIf the following groups or accounts are not defined for the \"Deny log on locally\" right, this is a finding.\n\nDomain Systems Only:\nEnterprise Admins Group\nDomain Admins Group\n\nPrivileged Access Workstations (PAWs) dedicated to the management of Active Directory are exempt from denying the Enterprise Admins and Domain Admins groups. (See the Windows Privileged Access Workstation STIG for PAW requirements.)\n\nAll Systems:\nGuests Group","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Inappropriate granting of user rights can provide system, administrative, and other high-level capabilities.\n\nThe \"Deny log on locally\" right defines accounts that are prevented from logging on interactively.\n\nIn an Active Directory Domain, denying logons to the Enterprise Admins and Domain Admins groups on lower trust systems helps mitigate the risk of privilege escalation from credential theft attacks, which could lead to the compromise of an entire domain.\n\nThe Guests group must be assigned this right to prevent unauthenticated access.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-63877","SV-78367","CCI-000213"],"reference_identifier":"7413","uuid":"127f48c5-4d95-4120-9eff-28cdfa7092df","stig_uuid":"af950999-fa42-4c61-9340-039117433de8","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Windows10_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 3BD51BE5EABEC02FB79EE5CECC93717C7B886430\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'The Deny log on locally user right on workstations must be configured to prevent access from highly privileged domain accounts on domain systems and unauthenticated access on all systems.' matches the expected value on the Windows 10 workstation."},{"group_id_src":"V-220972","group_tree":[{"id":"V-220972","title":"SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-220972","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048","rule_id_src":"SV-220972r1137691_rule","rule_id":"SV-220972","rule_version":"WN10-UR-000090","rule_title":"The Deny log on through Remote Desktop Services user right on Windows 10 workstations must at a minimum be configured to prevent access from highly privileged domain accounts and local accounts on domain systems and unauthenticated access on all systems.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> User Rights Assignment >> \"Deny log on through Remote Desktop Services\" to include the following.\n\nIf Remote Desktop Services is not used by the organization, assign the Everyone group this right to prevent all access.\n\nDomain Systems Only:\nEnterprise Admins group\nDomain Admins group\nLocal account (see Note below)\n\nAll Systems:\nGuests group\n\nPrivileged Access Workstations (PAWs) dedicated to the management of Active Directory are exempt from denying the Enterprise Admins and Domain Admins groups. (See the Windows Privileged Access Workstation STIG for PAW requirements.)\n\nNote: \"Local account\" is a built-in security group used to assign user rights and permissions to all local accounts.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the effective setting in Local Group Policy Editor.\n\nRun \"gpedit.msc\".\n\nNavigate to Local Computer Policy >> Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> User Rights Assignment.\n\nIf the following groups or accounts are not defined for the \"Deny log on through Remote Desktop Services\" right, this is a finding:\n\nIf Remote Desktop Services is not used by the organization, the \"Everyone\" group can replace all of the groups listed below.\n\nDomain Systems Only:\nEnterprise Admins group\nDomain Admins group\nLocal account (see Note below)\n\nAll Systems:\nGuests group\n\nPrivileged Access Workstations (PAWs) dedicated to the management of Active Directory are exempt from denying the Enterprise Admins and Domain Admins groups. (See the Windows Privileged Access Workstation STIG for PAW requirements.)\n\nNote: \"Local account\" is a built-in security group used to assign user rights and permissions to all local accounts.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Inappropriate granting of user rights can provide system, administrative, and other high-level capabilities.\n\nThe \"Deny log on through Remote Desktop Services\" right defines the accounts that are prevented from logging on using Remote Desktop Services.\n\nIf Remote Desktop Services is not used by the organization, the Everyone group must be assigned this right to prevent all access.\n\nIn an Active Directory Domain, denying logons to the Enterprise Admins and Domain Admins groups on lower trust systems helps mitigate the risk of privilege escalation from credential theft attacks, which could lead to the compromise of an entire domain.\n\nLocal accounts on domain-joined systems must also be assigned this right to decrease the risk of lateral movement resulting from credential theft attacks.\n\nThe Guests group must be assigned this right to prevent unauthenticated access.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-63879","SV-78369","CCI-000213","CCI-002314"],"reference_identifier":"8260","uuid":"eb8da136-33d4-4ff2-8641-976928b25218","stig_uuid":"af950999-fa42-4c61-9340-039117433de8","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Windows10_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 5CBFFAFC38E28E16998ADA1EA66C8AFD6836354E\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'The Deny log on through Remote Desktop Services user right on Windows 10 workstations must at a minimum be configured to prevent access from highly privileged domain accounts and local accounts on domain systems and unauthenticated access on all systems.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows 10 workstation."},{"group_id_src":"V-220973","group_tree":[{"id":"V-220973","title":"SRG-OS-000324-GPOS-00125","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-220973","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000324-GPOS-00125","rule_id_src":"SV-220973r958726_rule","rule_id":"SV-220973","rule_version":"WN10-UR-000095","rule_title":"The Enable computer and user accounts to be trusted for delegation user right must not be assigned to any groups or accounts.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> User Rights Assignment >> \"Enable computer and user accounts to be trusted for delegation\" to be defined but containing no entries (blank).","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the effective setting in Local Group Policy Editor.\nRun \"gpedit.msc\".\n\nNavigate to Local Computer Policy >> Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> User Rights Assignment.\n\nIf any groups or accounts are granted the \"Enable computer and user accounts to be trusted for delegation\" user right, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Inappropriate granting of user rights can provide system, administrative, and other high level capabilities.\n\nThe \"Enable computer and user accounts to be trusted for delegation\" user right allows the \"Trusted for Delegation\" setting to be changed. This could potentially allow unauthorized users to impersonate other users.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-63881","SV-78371","CCI-002235"],"reference_identifier":"2080","uuid":"e87d5faa-a0b8-4ec0-a447-f682c918e7a7","stig_uuid":"af950999-fa42-4c61-9340-039117433de8","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Windows10_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 7769583B522C21C67628A18BEB40F04EBE16EE9D\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'The Enable computer and user accounts to be trusted for delegation user right must not be assigned to any groups or accounts.' matches the expected value on the Windows 10 workstation."},{"group_id_src":"V-220974","group_tree":[{"id":"V-220974","title":"SRG-OS-000324-GPOS-00125","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-220974","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000324-GPOS-00125","rule_id_src":"SV-220974r958726_rule","rule_id":"SV-220974","rule_version":"WN10-UR-000100","rule_title":"The Force shutdown from a remote system user right must only be assigned to the Administrators group.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> User Rights Assignment >> \"Force shutdown from a remote system\" to only include the following groups or accounts:\n\nAdministrators","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the effective setting in Local Group Policy Editor.\nRun \"gpedit.msc\".\n\nNavigate to Local Computer Policy >> Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> User Rights Assignment.\n\nIf any groups or accounts other than the following are granted the \"Force shutdown from a remote system\" user right, this is a finding:\n\nAdministrators","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Inappropriate granting of user rights can provide system, administrative, and other high level capabilities.\n\nAccounts with the \"Force shutdown from a remote system\" user right can remotely shut down a system which could result in a DoS.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-78373","V-63883","CCI-002235"],"reference_identifier":"5418","uuid":"3825e087-17b1-405d-8694-8117c37ace83","stig_uuid":"af950999-fa42-4c61-9340-039117433de8","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Windows10_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: CA21C7B8486970A25D191CC1FC5C3FBE2CA1B848\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'The Force shutdown from a remote system user right must only be assigned to the Administrators group.' was not present or did not match the expected value on th