istrators group.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows 10 workstation."},{"group_id_src":"V-220981","group_tree":[{"id":"V-220981","title":"SRG-OS-000324-GPOS-00125","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-220981","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000324-GPOS-00125","rule_id_src":"SV-220981r958726_rule","rule_id":"SV-220981","rule_version":"WN10-UR-000150","rule_title":"The Profile single process user right must only be assigned to the Administrators group.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> User Rights Assignment >> \"Profile single process\" to only include the following groups or accounts:\n\nAdministrators","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the effective setting in Local Group Policy Editor.\nRun \"gpedit.msc\".\n\nNavigate to Local Computer Policy >> Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> User Rights Assignment.\n\nIf any groups or accounts other than the following are granted the \"Profile single process\" user right, this is a finding:\n\nAdministrators","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Inappropriate granting of user rights can provide system, administrative, and other high level capabilities.\n\nAccounts with the \"Profile single process\" user right can monitor non-system processes performance. An attacker could potentially use this to identify processes to attack.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-78425","V-63935","CCI-002235"],"reference_identifier":"9016","uuid":"f99d84c1-4060-4789-945d-d801264252b7","stig_uuid":"af950999-fa42-4c61-9340-039117433de8