es":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-63939","SV-78429","CCI-002235"],"reference_identifier":"6921","uuid":"bf71f77a-5651-4506-bce4-98fe2eaa5048","stig_uuid":"af950999-fa42-4c61-9340-039117433de8","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Windows10_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 3CCDD5ED0CEC02C223338011CFB5DC20194703B9\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'The Restore files and directories user right must only be assigned to the Administrators group.' matches the expected value on the Windows 10 workstation."},{"group_id_src":"V-220983","group_tree":[{"id":"V-220983","title":"SRG-OS-000324-GPOS-00125","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-220983","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000324-GPOS-00125","rule_id_src":"SV-220983r958726_rule","rule_id":"SV-220983","rule_version":"WN10-UR-000165","rule_title":"The Take ownership of files or other objects user right must only be assigned to the Administrators group.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> User Rights Assignment >> \"Take ownership of files or other objects\" to only include the following groups or accounts:\n\nAdministrators","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the effective setting in Local Group Policy Editor.\nRun \"gpedit.msc\".\n\nNavigate to Local Computer Policy >> Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> User Rights Assignment.\n\nIf any groups or accounts other than the following are granted the \"Take ownership of files or other objects\" user right, this is a finding:\n\nAdministrators","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Inappropriate granting of user rights can provide system, administrative, and other high level capabilities.\n\nAccounts with the \"Take ownership of files or other objects\" user right can take ownership of objects and make changes.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-78431","V-63941","CCI-002235"],"reference_identifier":"5491","uuid":"ccf8a93c-73f1-4731-a297-a4ede8f0b13c","stig_uuid":"af950999-fa42-4c61-9340-039117433de8","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Windows10_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 904497BEF82462BF9419991C91C6FDA05477628F\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'The Take ownership of files or other objects user right must only be assigned to the Administrators group.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows 10 workstation."},{"group_id_src":"V-250319","group_tree":[{"id":"V-250319","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-250319","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-250319r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-250319","rule_version":"WN10-CC-000050","rule_title":"Hardened UNC paths must be defined to require mutual authentication and integrity for at least the \\\\*\\SYSVOL and \\\\*\\NETLOGON shares.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> Network >> Network Provider >> \"Hardened UNC Paths\" to \"Enabled\" with at least the following configured in \"Hardened UNC Paths:\" (click the \"Show\" button to display).\n\nValue Name: \\\\*\\SYSVOL\nValue: RequireMutualAuthentication=1, RequireIntegrity=1\n\nValue Name: \\\\*\\NETLOGON\nValue: RequireMutualAuthentication=1, RequireIntegrity=1","weight":"10.0","check_content":"This requirement is applicable to domain-joined systems. For standalone or nondomain-joined systems, this is NA.\n\nIf the following registry values do not exist or are not configured as specified, this is a finding.\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Windows\\NetworkProvider\\HardenedPaths\\\n\nValue Name: \\\\*\\NETLOGON\nValue Type: REG_SZ\nValue: RequireMutualAuthentication=1, RequireIntegrity=1\n\nValue Name: \\\\*\\SYSVOL\nValue Type: REG_SZ\nValue: RequireMutualAuthentication=1, RequireIntegrity=1\n\nAdditional entries would not be a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Additional security requirements are applied to Universal Naming Convention (UNC) paths specified in Hardened UNC paths before allowing access to them. This aids in preventing tampering with or spoofing of connections to these paths.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-63577","SV-78067","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2656","uuid":"eead6b51-7d7f-42f7-bb51-7f8ee5971043","stig_uuid":"af950999-fa42-4c61-9340-039117433de8","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Windows10_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 40F1F1104A515EFD36883EE77D203CD182F65071\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Hardened UNC paths must be defined to require mutual authentication and integrity for at least the \\\\*\\SYSVOL and \\\\*\\NETLOGON shares.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows 10 workstation."},{"group_id_src":"V-252896","group_tree":[{"id":"V-252896","title":"SRG-OS-000041-GPOS-00019","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-252896","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000041-GPOS-00019","rule_id_src":"SV-252896r958420_rule","rule_id":"SV-252896","rule_version":"WN10-CC-000327","rule_title":"PowerShell Transcription must be enabled on Windows 10.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> Windows Components >> Windows PowerShell >> \"Turn on PowerShell Transcription\" to \"Enabled\".\n\nSpecify the Transcript output directory to point to a Central Log Server or another secure location to prevent user access.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding.\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Windows\\PowerShell\\Transcription\\\n\nValue Name: EnableTranscripting\n\nValue Type: REG_DWORD\nValue: 1","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Maintaining an audit trail of system activity logs can help identify configuration errors, troubleshoot service disruptions, and analyze compromises that have occurred, as well as detect attacks. Audit logs are necessary to provide a trail of evidence in case the system or network is compromised. Collecting this data is essential for analyzing the security of information assets and detecting signs of suspicious and unexpected behavior.\n\nEnabling PowerShell Transcription will record detailed information from the processing of PowerShell commands and scripts. This can provide additional detail when malware has run on a system.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000132","CCI-000134"],"reference_identifier":"2819","uuid":"5158ba4b-9f27-4c20-bc54-6fb17a0fd1ee","stig_uuid":"af950999-fa42-4c61-9340-039117433de8","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Windows10_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 6ED9F520D07178653D26FB3B1D058FE7B9B4420B\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'PowerShell Transcription must be enabled on Windows 10.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows 10 workstation."},{"group_id_src":"V-252903","group_tree":[{"id":"V-252903","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-252903","severity":"low","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-252903r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-252903","rule_version":"WN10-CC-000080","rule_title":"Virtualization-based protection of code integrity must be enabled.","fix_text":"Virtualization-based security currently cannot be implemented in VDIs due to specific supporting requirements, including a TPM, UEFI with Secure Boot, and the capability to run the Hyper-V feature within the virtual desktop.\n\nFor VDIs where the virtual desktop instance is deleted or refreshed upon logoff, this is NA.\n\nConfigure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> System >> Device Guard >> \"Turn On Virtualization Based Security\" to \"Enabled\" with \"Enabled with UEFI lock\" or \"Enabled without lock\" selected for \"Virtualization Based Protection of Code Integrity:\".\n\n\"Enabled with UEFI lock\" is preferred as more secure; however, it cannot be turned off remotely through a group policy change if there is an issue.\n\n\"Enabled without lock\" will allow this to be turned off remotely while testing for issues.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Confirm virtualization-based protection of code integrity.\n\nFor devices that support the virtualization based security (VBS) feature for protection of code integrity, this must be enabled. If the system meets the hardware, firmware, and compatible device driver dependencies for enabling virtualization-based protection of code integrity but it is not enabled, this is a CAT II finding.\n\nVirtualization based security currently cannot be implemented in virtual desktop implementations (VDI) due to specific supporting requirements including a TPM, UEFI with Secure Boot, and the capability to run the Hyper-V feature within the virtual desktop.\n\nFor VDIs where the virtual desktop instance is deleted or refreshed upon logoff, this is NA.\n\nRun \"PowerShell\" with elevated privileges (run as administrator).\nEnter the following:\n\"Get-CimInstance -ClassName Win32_DeviceGuard -Namespace root\\Microsoft\\Windows\\DeviceGuard\"\n\nIf \"SecurityServicesRunning\" does not include a value of \"2\" (e.g., \"{1, 2}\"), this is a finding.\n\nAlternately:\n\nRun \"System Information\".\n\nUnder \"System Summary\", verify the following:\nIf \"Virtualization-based Security Services Running\" does not list \"Hypervisor enforced Code Integrity\", this is finding.\n\nThe policy settings referenced in the Fix section will configure the following registry value. However due to hardware requirements, the registry value alone does not ensure proper function.\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Windows\\DeviceGuard\\\n\nValue Name: HypervisorEnforcedCodeIntegrity\nValue Type: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000001 (1) (Enabled with UEFI lock), or 0x00000002 (2) (Enabled without lock)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Virtualization-based protection of code integrity enforces kernel mode memory protections and protects Code Integrity validation paths. This isolates the processes from the rest of the operating system and can only be accessed by privileged system software.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2620","uuid":"3461f32c-f918-419a-a90f-251fe7bd6e40","stig_uuid":"af950999-fa42-4c61-9340-039117433de8","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Windows10_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 9F5F73A086A4B0E5CDEA9CF1347D1C3CD37727CE\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Virtualization-based protection of code integrity must be enabled.' matches the expected value on the Windows 10 workstation."},{"group_id_src":"V-256894","group_tree":[{"id":"V-256894","title":"SRG-OS-000185-GPOS-00079","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-256894","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000185-GPOS-00079","rule_id_src":"SV-256894r958552_rule","rule_id":"SV-256894","rule_version":"WN10-CC-000391","rule_title":"Internet Explorer must be disabled for Windows 10.","fix_text":"For Windows 10 semi-annual channel, remove or disable the IE11 application. \n\nTo disable IE11 as a standalone browser:\n\nSet the policy value for \"Computer Configuration/Administrative Templates/Windows Components/Internet Explorer/Disable Internet Explorer 11 as a standalone browser\" to \"Enabled\" with the option value set to \"Never\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Determine if IE11 is installed or enabled on Windows 10 semi-annual channel.\n\nIf IE11 is installed or not disabled on Windows 10 semi-annual channel, this is a finding.\n\nIf IE11 is installed on a unsupported operating system and is enabled or installed, this is a finding.\n\nFor more information, visit: https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/lifecycle/faq/internet-explorer-microsoft-edge#what-is-the-lifecycle-policy-for-internet-explorer-","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Internet Explorer 11 (IE11) is no longer supported on Windows 10 semi-annual channel.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"6617","uuid":"9ea1d217-a0cb-45d0-8b3b-1ff5e96c96f3","stig_uuid":"af950999-fa42-4c61-9340-039117433de8","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Windows10_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 280907F458A8D55A28CD2E6BB7A4E6876EE0A4BF\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Internet Explorer must be disabled for Windows 10.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows 10 workstation."},{"group_id_src":"V-257589","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257589","title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257589","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","rule_id_src":"SV-257589r958412_rule","rule_id":"SV-257589","rule_version":"WN10-AU-000585","rule_title":"Windows 10 must have command line process auditing events enabled for failures.","fix_text":"Go to Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Advanced Audit Policy Configuration >>System Audit Policies >> Detailed Tracking >> Audit Process Creation is set to \"failure\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Ensure Audit Process Creation auditing has been enabled: \n\nComputer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Advanced Audit Policy Configuration >>System Audit Policies >> Detailed Tracking >> Audit Process Creation\". \n\nIf \"Audit Process Creation\" is not set to \"Failure\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"When this policy setting is enabled, the operating system generates audit events when a process fails to start and the name of the program or user that created it.\n\nThese audit events can assist in understanding how a computer is being used and tracking user activity.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-002234"],"reference_identifier":"5224","uuid":"2a98806c-018b-4c7d-a2cb-3b53e158f68e","stig_uuid":"af950999-fa42-4c61-9340-039117433de8","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Windows10_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 947FF561C7C94A83F1EF85B4E3EC72939B6CEBE3\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Windows 10 must have command line process auditing events enabled for failures.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows 10 workstation."},{"group_id_src":"V-257593","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257593","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257593","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-257593r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-257593","rule_version":"WN10-00-000395","rule_title":"Windows 10 must not have portproxy enabled or in use.","fix_text":"Contact the Administrator to run \"netsh interface portproxy delete\" with elevation. Remove any enabled portproxies that may be configured.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Check the registry key for existence of proxied ports:\nHKLM\\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Services\\PortProxy\\. \n\nIf the key contains v4tov4\\tcp\\ or is populated v4tov4\\tcp\\, this is a finding. \n\nRun \"netsh interface portproxy show all\". \n\nIf the command displays any results, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Having portproxy enabled or configured in Windows 10 could allow a man-in-the-middle attack.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000381"],"reference_identifier":"4789","uuid":"40c6e031-5bc5-45ca-a733-e478a2332a22","stig_uuid":"af950999-fa42-4c61-9340-039117433de8","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Windows10_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 1CC2F79D2D08DC744AEF9B14848D2C7B0A1E85B8\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Windows 10 must not have portproxy enabled or in use.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows 10 workstation."},{"group_id_src":"V-268315","group_tree":[{"id":"V-268315","title":"SRG-OS-000096-GPOS-00050","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-268315","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000096-GPOS-00050","rule_id_src":"SV-268315r1135269_rule","rule_id":"SV-268315","rule_version":"WN10-00-000107","rule_title":"Copilot must be disabled for Windows 10.","fix_text":"Open PowerShell as an administrator. Run the following command:\n\nGet-AppxPackage -AllUsers *CoPilot* | Remove-AppxPackage -AllUsers","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Run the following PowerShell command as an administrator:\n\nGet-AppxPackage -AllUsers | Where-Object { $_.Name -like \"*Copilot*\" }\n\nIf Microsoft.Copilot displays, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Some features may communicate with the vendor, sending system information or downloading data or components for the feature. Turning off this capability will prevent potentially sensitive information from being sent outside the enterprise and uncontrolled updates to the system.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000382"],"reference_identifier":"5334","uuid":"ef82e9ab-a908-484d-b586-fa8907f7d5f6","stig_uuid":"af950999-fa42-4c61-9340-039117433de8","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Windows10_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 89534C321116F901656D558AF5C5CD1B70342529\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Copilot must be disabled for Windows 10.' matches the expected value on the Windows 10 workstation."},{"group_id_src":"V-268319","group_tree":[{"id":"V-268319","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-268319","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-268319r1135263_rule","rule_id":"SV-268319","rule_version":"WN10-CC-000063","rule_title":"Windows 10 systems must use either Group Policy or an approved Mobile Device Management (MDM) product to enforce STIG compliance.","fix_text":"Configure the Windows 10 system to use either Group Policy or an approved MDM product to enforce STIG compliance.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the Windows 10 system is receiving policy from either Group Policy or an MDM with the following steps:\n\nFrom a command line or PowerShell:\n\ngpresult /R\nOS Configuration: Member Workstation\n\nIf the system is not being managed by GPO, ask the administrator to indicate which MDM is managing the device.\n\nFrom PowerShell: Get-Service -Name \"IntuneManagementExtension\"\n\nIf the Windows 10 system is not receiving policy from either Group Policy or an MDM, this is a finding.\n\nThis is NA for standalone, nondomain-joined systems.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without Windows 10 systems being managed, devices could be rogue and become targets of an attacker.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"1601","uuid":"bd836c0f-ac4c-4d77-8f8e-d9fa3c1a8897","stig_uuid":"af950999-fa42-4c61-9340-039117433de8","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Windows10_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 4EBE1950A8E2C0B86EBFB4383CD2C44CDDC20B03\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Windows 10 systems must use either Group Policy or an approved Mobile Device Management (MDM) product to enforce STIG compliance.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows 10 workstation."},{"group_id_src":"V-278918","group_tree":[{"id":"V-278918","title":"SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-278918","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031","rule_id_src":"SV-278918r1135272_rule","rule_id":"SV-278918","rule_version":"WN10-AU-000581","rule_title":"Windows 10 must be configured to audit file system failures.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Advanced Audit Policy Configuration >> System Audit Policies >> Object Access >> \"Audit File System\" with \"Failure\" selected.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that Audit File System auditing has been enabled: \n\nComputer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Advanced Audit Policy Configuration >> System Audit Policies >> Object Access >> Audit File System. \n\nIf \"Audit File System\" is not set to \"Failure\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Maintaining an audit trail of system activity logs can help identify configuration errors, troubleshoot service disruptions, and analyze compromises that have occurred, as well as detect attacks. Audit logs are necessary to provide a trail of evidence in case the system or network is compromised. Collecting this data is essential for analyzing the security of information assets and detecting signs of suspicious and unexpected behavior. Credential validation records events related to validation tests on credentials for a user account logon.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"4459","uuid":"66724d42-71b2-4302-9b56-76fced7af317","stig_uuid":"af950999-fa42-4c61-9340-039117433de8","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Windows10_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 9FBE65E69DE3766AF1F8D64FBC093CE2BB2B1FB3\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows 10 must be configured to audit file system failures.' matches the expected value on the Windows 10 workstation."},{"group_id_src":"V-278919","group_tree":[{"id":"V-278919","title":"SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-278919","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031","rule_id_src":"SV-278919r1135275_rule","rule_id":"SV-278919","rule_version":"WN10-AU-000582","rule_title":"Windows 10 must be configured to audit file system successes.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Advanced Audit Policy Configuration >> System Audit Policies >> Object Access >> \"Audit File System\" with \"Success\" selected.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that Audit File System auditing has been enabled: \n\nComputer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Advanced Audit Policy Configuration >> System Audit Policies >> Object Access >> Audit File System. \n\nIf \"Audit File System\" is not set to \"Success\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Maintaining an audit trail of system activity logs can help identify configuration errors, troubleshoot service disruptions, and analyze compromises that have occurred, as well as detect attacks. Audit logs are necessary to provide a trail of evidence in case the system or network is compromised. Collecting this data is essential for analyzing the security of information assets and detecting signs of suspicious and unexpected behavior. Credential validation records events related to validation tests on credentials for a user account logon.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"8068","uuid":"0c164aba-3782-4dee-b6d8-4782f19470ec","stig_uuid":"af950999-fa42-4c61-9340-039117433de8","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Windows10_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: DB96E0971AD78AC64C03A1B0A7DF43B736118921\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'Windows 10 must be configured to audit file system successes.' is not present or not in use on this the Windows 10 workstation."},{"group_id_src":"V-278920","group_tree":[{"id":"V-278920","title":"SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-278920","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031","rule_id_src":"SV-278920r1135278_rule","rule_id":"SV-278920","rule_version":"WN10-AU-000583","rule_title":"Windows 10 must be configured to audit handle manipulation failures.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Advanced Audit Policy Configuration >> System Audit Policies >> Object Access >> \"Audit Handle Manipulation\" with \"Failure\" selected.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that Audit Handle Manipulation auditing has been enabled: \n\nComputer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Advanced Audit Policy Configuration >> System Audit Policies >> Object Access >> Audit Handle Manipulation. \n\nIf \"Audit Handle Manipulation\" is not set to \"Failure\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Maintaining an audit trail of system activity logs can help identify configuration errors, troubleshoot service disruptions, and analyze compromises that have occurred, as well as detect attacks. Audit logs are necessary to provide a trail of evidence in case the system or network is compromised. Collecting this data is essential for analyzing the security of information assets and detecting signs of suspicious and unexpected behavior. Credential validation records events related to validation tests on credentials for a user account logon.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"6040","uuid":"dc14ce94-b05d-4f86-80aa-9ad0c3f7a9d2","stig_uuid":"af950999-fa42-4c61-9340-039117433